In geometry, an 'icosahedron' ( or ) is a polyhedron with 20 triangular faces,
30 edges and 12 vertices. A 'regular icosahedron' with identical equilateral
faces is often meant because of its geometrical significance as one of the five
Platonic solids, all regular polyhedrons including the regular tetrahedron, the
cube or regular hexahedron, the regular octahedron, and the regular dodecahedron
with 4, 6, 8 and 12 identical faces, respectively.

It has five triangular faces meeting at each vertex. It can be represented by
its vertex figure as 3.3.3.3.3 or 3 5, and also by SchlÃ¤fli symbol
{3,5}. It is the dual of the dodecahedron, which is represented by {5,3}, having
three pentagonal faces around each vertex.
